                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>Llygadwy Stone <term>rejected monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/">CPAT Regional Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">665</idno></p>
                                    <material type="stone">Stone type unknown</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                    <dimensions unit="m" source="MAC1945">
                                        <height>1.68</height>
                                        <width>0.43</width>
                                        <depth>0.48</depth>
                                    </dimensions></support>
                                <condition>No inscriptions are visible on the stone today. The inscriptions recorded by Macalister (1945, 324) were fragmentary as it was assumed that cattle rubbing had removed further letters from the stone. According to Macalister (1945, 324) only three letters of the ogham inscription could be seen and the roman inscription was <q>so completely worn down by cattle and weather, that it was quite impossible to feel any certainty about</q> the letters. RCAHMW recorded scratches on the stone but these are suggested to be from wire chafing.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">Macalister (1945, 324) suggested the presence of an ogham inscription on the north-west angle of the stone as well as a roman-letter inscription on the south-face of the stone <q>below the modern socket cut in the middle of the face 1.3m above the ground</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 542). However, Macalister (1945, 324) stated that his suggestion of the presence of the roman-letter inscription was given <q>without any conviction</q> (see also Macalister 1922, 219). If the inscriptions were present, the ogham likely would have read vertically upwards and the roman-letter inscription likely would have read vertically downwards but this is uncertain. </layout>                            
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>There is no evidence to indicate how these alleged inscriptions might have been carved, so the execution technique remains <rs type="execution" key="other">unknown</rs>. 
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
